1. Development Mode (Local Machine)

If you're just developing and want to run your Django app locally (perhaps with Cloudflare Tunnel), follow these steps:

1.1 Activate Virtual Environment (if using one):

First, activate your virtual environment if you're using one. If you're not using a virtual environment, skip this step.

source /path/to/your/virtualenv/bin/activate

1.2 Run Django Development Server:

Start the Django development server, binding it to 0.0.0.0 so it can be accessed externally (including through the Cloudflare Tunnel).

python manage.py runserver 0.0.0.0:8000


This command will start Django on port 8000, and it will be accessible via the public IP of your machine, or localhost.

1.3 Run Cloudflare Tunnel (if exposing externally via Cloudflare):

If you’re using Cloudflare Tunnel to expose the app to the internet, run the following command after you’ve created and configured the tunnel:

cloudflared tunnel run <your-tunnel-id>


Make sure that Cloudflare Tunnel is running and has the correct credentials and DNS settings to forward traffic to your local Django server
